Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Peel and slice the @potatoes{600%grams} into ½ cm thick rounds.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @shallot{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Place a #pot{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When the oil is hot, fry the garlic for ~{1%minute}.

Add the potato, @Hello Muscat{2%sachets}, @creme fraiche{110%grams} and @milk{125%ml} or water (per 2P). Season with @salt{1/2%tsp} (per 2P) and @pepper{1/2%tsp} (per 2P). Mix well.

Bring to a boil then cover and lower heat to medium. Stir often to prevent sticking.

Simmer until potatoes are parboiled, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Score the skin of the @Irish Duck Breast{350%grams}.

Place in a cold #pan{}, skin-side down.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw duck and its packaging. Duck is cooked when browned on the outside.

Turn the heat to medium-high and sear until the skin is a golden brown colour, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Turn and cook for another ~{2-3%minutes}. Reserve the duck fat to use later.

Transfer the potatoes and sauce to an appropriately-sized #oven dish{}.

Pop into the oven to bake until cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Pop the duck breasts into another oven dish and cook for another ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @salad leaves{120%grams}, then thinly slice or tear into bite-sized pieces.

Place the pan with duck fat over medium-high heat.

Add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add a splash of water and stir well to make a sauce with the cooking juices.

Just before serving, mix a drizzle of @oil{to taste} with the @balsamic vinegar{1%sachet}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} in a #salad bowl{}. Just before serving, add the salad and toss to combine.

Allow the duck to rest for a few mins, slice and divide between plates.

Pour the shallot sauce over it.

Serve the dauphinoise and salad alongside.